<HL> )HL    MARKETING:
For More Men, Old Gray Hair
Ain't What It Appears to Be
---
By Ronald Alsop
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 07/30/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> FOOD &amp; BEVERAGE, HOUSEHOLD GOODS, SUPERMARKETS, TOBACCO (FAB)
MARKETING, ADVERTISING (MKT) </IN>
<TEXT>
   SINCE 1961, Combe Inc. has been marketing Grecian Formula 16 as a way for men to subtly tint gray hair. 
The product works gradually over three to four weeks so that friends may not even suspect the hair has been colored. 
After all, what would people think if they knew a man dyed his hair? 

   But attitudes change. 
The 1980s man, it seems, can now act like a peacock and color his hair without feeling ashamed. 
This month, Combe is launching a second hair coloring product called Just for Men that boldly transforms gray hair to brown in just five minutes. 
The instant change is, of course, apparent to everyone. 
"There's not the big stigma anymore about coloring your hair," says Dominic DeMain, vice president of marketing for Combe's hair-care products. 
"Men feel younger and want to look it. 
They tell us they want an immediate color change if they have a job interview or a date with a new girlfriend." 

   Combe, in fact, believes times have never been better for selling men's hair dye. 
For one thing, the company finds that many middle-aged men today worry about competition on the job from aggressive young baby boomers. 
Gray hair, they feel, is a handicap, and they are increasingly willing to consider dyeing it. 
In addition, Combe expects Just for Men to benefit from the fact that many older men admire President Reagan, who has barely a speck of silver showing at age 76. 
"The market potential is simply huge," declares Mr. DeMain. 
"We figure only 3.5 million of the 33 million men with gray hair currently use a color treatment." 

   THE MARKET LOOKS even more promising five to 10 years from now. 
Combe is betting that male baby boomers, most of whom are in their 20s and 30s, will not grow old gracefully. 
Because these young men so value their health and physical appearance, Combe and other marketers expect them to get face lifts, exercise to stay trim, buy anti-baldness products -- and color the gray away. 

   But that's a debatable point. 
Some marketing consultants believe honesty will ultimately prevail over vanity. 
They predict that Americans will become less obsessed with a youthful appearance and will prefer a more natural look. 
"I don't believe men will hide the truth with hair coloring," says Carol Colman, a partner at Inferential Focus, a New York research firm. 
"What I see coming is more honesty about who you are." 

   Even now, many men remain reluctant to tint their hair. 
A recent survey of 1,000 middle-aged men revealed that 43% believe it's "OK" to color gray hair, but the majority disapprove, or at least have some reservations. 
Perhaps more than anything else, men fear that a home coloring kit will give their hair a greenish or purplish cast. 
Or something worse. 
"Many men have tried home products and ended up with orange hair," says Patrice Serrani, grooming editor for GQ magazine. 
"It's probably best for a man to let a professional at a salon teach him to use hair coloring." 

   SALES OF home hair coloring products specifically targeted to men total about $47 million a year. 
But that doesn't fully cover the amount of money men spend on home hair dyes. 

   Cosmair Inc. receives many inquiries from men wondering whether they can use the company's L'Oreal colors for women. 
"We tell them, 'Of course you can,'" says James Viera, a vice president at Cosmair. 
"We're all humans with the same kind of hair." 
Bristol-Myers Co. similarly finds that men use its Clairol Loving Care and Nice 'n Easy, often borrowing them from wives or girlfriends. 

   Combe hopes Just for Men, which features photos of virile young men on the package, will be a welcome alternative to those women's brands. 
"Men feel a little embarrassed going to the cash register with products that show only pictures of women on the boxes," says Mr. DeMain, the marketing executive at Combe. 

   Just for Men is being shipped to stores now, and in August, a TV commercial for the brand will begin running, featuring a typical "before and after" demonstration. 
The hair coloring is the culmination of 10 years of development and testing, an unusually slow process for a consumer product. 
Why so long? 
"We had to come up with colors that blended in naturally, and that is complicated chemistry," explains Herbert Lapidus, director of research and development. 
"The product also had to be quick and easy to shampoo in so it wouldn't interfere with men's normal grooming regimen. 
They won't sit for 40 minutes with goop on their hair the way women do." 

   WITH A NEW PRODUCT like Just for Men, there's always the danger that it will cannibalize sales of Combe's other coloring product, Grecian Formula. 
But the company isn't fretting because it believes Just for Men's faster action and more noticeable results will appeal to a different type of customer. 
In fact, Combe says, Grecian Formula's sales rose 14% in cities where Just for Men was test marketed. 

   Just for Men faces little competition from other marketers. 
The one large company in the market -- Bristol-Myers's Clairol subsidiary -- isn't allocating any advertising funds to its Great Day color gel for men this year. 
And most of Combe's other competitors are small companies with small marketing budgets. 
For example, Majestic Drug Co., which sells Youthair and Groom Away Gray for men, says it can afford only a little magazine advertising. 
Another gradual coloring treatment, EverYouth, also has suffered from low visibility. 
But the marketer of EverYouth plans to step up advertising this fall, using ex-boxing champion Rocky Graziano as spokesman. 
The ad slogan: "I knocked out gray with EverYouth." 

