<LEADPARA>  WHY DO YOU NEVER SEE A PARTIALly gray hair? Why are they never gray at the
root and dark at the tip?;      GRAY HAIRS SEEM TO HAVE THIS MYSTErious way of
arriving full-blown on your head, neatly interspersed among dark ones. It is
as though the follicle emits some kind of fiendish secretion that, overnight,
travels the length of the hair and dyes it gray or white.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THAT'S WHY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But what really happens is, the pigment in a given follicle is slowly
diluted as a person gets older. There is no sudden cutoff of pigment, and so
you never see a hair that goes abruptly from black to white or from brown to
gray. The transition is usually too subtle to notice unless you're really
checking yourself out.;    "You should be able to see a hair that has both
dark and light in it," says Andrew Atton, dermatologist at the Johns Hopkins
school of medicine.;    Now then: What about Marie Antoinette, who supposedly
went gray overnight as she awaited execution? How did that happen?;    In
Marie's case, the answer may be simply that she was locked up for a while and
ran out of her hair coloring. In other, more credible cases of extremely rapid
graying, what may happen is that the pigmented hairs fall out over the course
of a couple of weeks, leaving the white or gray hairs that are already there.
According to the textbook Diseases of the Hair and Scalp, by Arthur Rook and
Rodney Dawber, this may be a quirky result of the hair follicle disease
"alopecia areata," but it is basically still a mystery.;    It's more fun to
think Marie was just scared pigmentless.;     GUESS AGAIN; LOTS OF PEOPLE,
FROM DOUGLAS FAIRBANKS to Kevin Costner, have played Robin Hood. Both Sean
Connery and his son Jason have played him. Which of the following played Robin
Hood's son in the movies?;    A. John Derek; B. Douglas Fairbanks, Jr.; C.
Richard Greene; D. Richard Todd; E. Cornel Wilde (Answer below); ANSWER: A, in
Rogues of Sherwood Forest (1950), and E, in Bandit of Sherwood Forest (1946).  </TEXT>
