<HEAD>Prison Beauty Shop Gives Inmates Reason to Feel Good</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLDWATER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chatter resembles that of any beauty
salon. Women tease each other about their ages and their graying
hair as they sit under hair dryers and flip through timeworn
magazines.
   Posters of the latest hairstyles cover the battered walls, and
the pungent odor of the solution used for permanents fills the air.
   The tools of the beauty trade at the medium-security
Florence-Crane Women's Facility are nothing special, but they're of
some concern. Scissors, electric razors and chemicals can be
dangerous - especially in the hands of convicted criminals.
   Some of these women are locked up for life. Some can receive no
visitors. But still, inmates say, the prison beauty shop serves an
essential purpose.
   ``Everyone feels better, even if they've had a bad day,'' said
beautician Diane Carter, serving 20 years on drug and escape
charges. ``It's just like going shopping - you get depressed and
you go shopping.''
   ``It's not a privilege. It's a necessity for a lot of us,'' said
Sherron Butler, who is serving up to 14 years for writing bad
checks and escape.
   ``We're also still human beings and if you love yourself, you're
going to take care of yourself. When I got here, I said, `Great,
they have a beauty shop. I can continue to be me.'''
   Butler was getting this season's favorite style, the $25 wave
nouveau. In addition to the curl, she often comes in to have her
hair colored - autumn mist is her shade - and to buy cocoa butter
lotion.
   Rather than chip off her nail polish, she can spend a quarter to
dip her fingers and toes in nail polish remover. Inmates can have
nail polish outside the shop, but the remover contains alcohol and
stays put.
   The shop has its regulars, but most inmates cut each other's
hair in the housing units, where they're permitted to check out
blunt-ended scissors.
   Each state prison has a hair care area where inmate barbers are
supervised by a civilian cosmetologist, said Gail Light, a
spokeswoman for the Michigan Department of Corrections.
   In federal prisons, basic haircuts are free, said Dan Dunne,
assistant public information officer for the U.S. Bureau of Prisons
in Washington, D.C. Inmates who want something special, like a perm
or dye, can buy the materials at a commissary and bring them to the
prison's cosmetology unit for application, he said.
   The beauty shop at the Florence-Crane facility is cramped. One
authentic cosmetology chair is joined by a host of outdated barber
equipment bought used or donated. Hairdryers line the wall near the
window sill, where a newly arrived air conditioner blows comfort on
feverish, summer days.
   Mildred Perry, one of four inmate beauticians, remembers
converting the space from junk room to beauty shop when she was
transferred to Florence-Crane in 1985.
   ``There was a desperate need for a beauty shop,'' said Perry,
who is serving a life term for second-degree murder. ``We knew the
self-esteem would go down. They didn't care about themselves any
more.
   ``This was the only chair, there was one working spigot with
cold water and one bucket. It just grew and grew. We had to get a
crochet needle to pull the hair through the cap for the first
frostin job we did.''
   Most of the cosmetology unit's operating costs are covered by
what they charge customers, and its prices are competitive with
outside shops. A price list hangs near the rinse sink: $14 for
``jazzing color,'' $20 for a frosted perm, $6 for hot oil and
condition treatment, $5 for a plain cut.
   Money never changes hands. Women contact the cosmetology unit
for an appointment, and the civilian cosmetologist, who operates
mostly as an observer, checks their accounts to make sure they have
enough.
   The shop in the main prison is open two days a week, and the
four prisoners serve about a dozen customers each day. An annex
salon is open Saturdays.
   Some of the workers had cosmetology experience before being sent
to the prison. Others picked it up in prison. Inmates have asked
for a certification program so they'll be able to get cosmetology
jobs when they leave prison, but there is no money to pay for it.
   The beauticians, who get $1.50 a day and a free hairdo a month,
must hand in their nurse-like smocks and are searched before they
leave work, said assistant deputy warden Terri Baker.
   No incidents other than minor thefts have been reported,
probably because corrections officers and the civilian
cosmetologist always are watching.
   Beautician Serena Gordon, serving a life term for second-degree
murder, said she's never been threatened with violence by a
customer who didn't like the way her hair turned out.
   She recalled a young woman with black hair who wanted it
frosted.
   ``When I got done, she just started crying,'' Gordon said. ``She
didn't realize it was going to make her look that old.''
   Gordon also gave a professional bleach job to another inmate
whose hair temporarily turned green.
   ``That time,'' she said, ``I cried.''
</TEXT>
