<HL> MARKETING:
Looking Back at Floppy Ads,
Men's Hair Coloring and More
---
By Ronald Alsop
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 12/31/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> BMY MDEST ACCOB
MARKETING, ADVERTISING (MKT)
ELECTRIC, ELECTRONICS, APPLIANCES (ELE)
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
BEVERAGES (BVG)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN>
<TEXT>
   NO DOUBT marketers will remember 1987 mostly for the stock market crash and its impact on consumer spending. 
But there were other lesser milestones in the world of marketing. 
It was the year in which Bud Light spokesdog Spuds MacKenzie became a media sensation . . . the TV network's prudish censors finally allowed women to wear bras in commercials . . . and an E.F. Hutton marketing executive tried to solve the brokerage firm's image and morale problems with a coloring book. 

   Those were just some of the topics covered here in recent months. 
Now on New Year's Eve, the marketing column updates a few of the subjects it explored in 1987: 

   THE REVIEWS ARE IN, and floppy disk advertising appears to be a hit. 
Both General Motors Corp.'s Buick division and Chase Manhattan Bank say they were quite pleased with the "software brochures" they used to reach personal-computer users. 
Chase put the sales spiel for its electronic funds transfer service on a computer disk, while a similar Buick disk included animated drawings of automobiles plus data about standard equipment, mileage and monthly car payments. 

   Buick had expected to distribute 20,000 disks to Apple computer users but ultimately mailed out 67,000. 
"We attracted many customers who aren't normally part of the Buick market," says Nancy Newell, manager of electronic product information for the car maker. 
"About 10% of the people we surveyed intended to buy a Buick after viewing the disk, and three-quarters of them were not current Buick owners." 
Next month, Buick will unveil even more elaborate software promoting its 1988 models. 

   While floppy disks are far from being an established medium, more advertisers are giving them a shot. 
SoftAd Group in Sausalito, Calif., has designed software to market Siemens Medical Systems' hospital equipment, and Creative Media Group in Parsippany, N.J., has developed a disk promoting Listerine to periodontists. 

   ---
   THERE'S ANOTHER NEW ENTRY in the $47 million men's hair-coloring market: Bristol-Myers Co.'s Clairol subsidiary is testing a foamy product called Option on the West Coast. 
It is dispensed from a can much like shaving cream and gradually covers the gray after several applications. 
Option follows close behind last summer's introduction of Just for Men, a fast-acting dye from Combe Inc. 

   Clairol's marketing officials agree with Combe executives that the men's coloring market should take off in a few years when more baby boomers start to gray. 
"We hope to develop the men's category with Option, but it's going to take patience because many men really don't want to color their hair," says Bill Susetka, group director of new business development at Clairol. 
He adds that Clairol doesn't believe men want the immediate, noticeable color change they would get with a product like Combe's Just for Men. 

   For its part, Combe says Just for Men is "doing fine." 
But the company won't disclose any sales results. 

   ---
   AFTER A SLOW START last spring, Adolph Coors Co. is making some heady market share gains in parts of New York and New Jersey. 
The company claims it has 6% to 8% of the upstate New York beer market, 7.5% to 9.5% in New York City and 14% to 18% in New Jersey. 
"We've got very good momentum after our first 10 months in these two big states," says Terry Nauslar, director of market expansion, "but we'll have to be even more focused and aggressive in 1988." 

   Indeed, beverage analysts note that Coors still is having difficulty penetrating New York's bars and restaurants. 
What's more, Mr. Nauslar says, Coors has riled Anheuser-Busch Cos. into action to defend Budweiser's market share. 
And he also frets that Corona Extra, a hot-selling Mexican beer, may roll into New York soon. 

   Pennsylvania and Delaware, meanwhile, are on tap to receive their initial Coors shipments in the first half of 1988. 
After that, Coors will have just one more frontier to invade: Indiana. 

   ---
   TWO AMBITIOUS PROJECTS for importing Israeli food into the U.S. aren't exactly cooking. 
A New York concern called Ficom International Inc. had planned to import a variety of gourmet foods from Israel and market them under the brand name Betavon. 
But Ficom didn't receive the financial assistance it expected from Israel, and Betavon remains just a name on paper. 
Ficom has filed suit in federal court against the Israeli Export Institute, charging breach of contract. 

   John Roberts, president of I/AM Importing, the other Israeli food venture, acknowledges that progress has been much slower than expected. 
But he's optimistic about 1988. 
In fact, he says, I/AM just began representing its first company and is now importing Israeli turkey products under the brand name Yarden. 

   ---
   FIFTEEN-SECOND COMMERCIALS keep gaining in popularity, accounting for 29% of network TV ads in the first nine months of 1987. 
That's up from 20% in the 1986 period, according to the TV Bureau of Advertising. 
A few national advertisers have switched entirely to 15s. 
For instance, the Ogilvy &amp; Mather ad agency just created an $18 million campaign for Pepperidge Farm that includes 13 different 15s. 
"We get more media exposure for our money," explains Ben Arno, a management supervisor at Ogilvy, "and we can focus on a lot more products and flavors with 13 separate ads." 

</TEXT>
