<LEADPARA>  Q How does fruit ripen once it is off the tree?;    A Fruit can ripen after it
is picked because everything necessary for ripening is either stored or made
inside the fruit. But that is true only if the fruit isn't picked too early.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Science &amp; Medicine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FRAGILE CHEMISTRY YIELDS SWEETNESS, COLOR
TASTIEST FRUITS ARE TREE-RIPENED  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Q&amp;A  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Four things happen to most ripening fruits: They sweeten, develop their
special flavors, soften and change color.;    All of these are biochemical
processes set off by a ripening hormone. In most non-citrus fruits, that
hormone is ethylene, and it is made inside the fruit itself, according to John
Labavitch, a biochemist at the University of California, Davis, who studies
the ripening process.;    As the fruit ripens, starches stored in the fruit
are converted to sugars. Acids are destroyed, which also adds to the
sweetness. But that's not all there is to taste. The ripening fruit also
produces a unique mix of flavor chemicals that make a peach taste like a
peach, and a pear like a pear.;    At the same time, the fruit grows soft,
thanks to special enzymes that partially break down the rigid walls
surrounding the fruit's cells.;    Other enzymes destroy the fruit's green
chlorophyll, and new pigments take the chlorophyll's place: Anthocyanins make
apples red and plums blue, and carotenoid pigments create the orange-red of a
ripe tomato.;    Fruits can ripen normally off the plant if they are fully
mature when they are picked, said Labavitch, but they may never get as sweet
as those that ripen on the plant, which continue to be infused with sugar as
they ripen. Fruit that is picked too young may not have developed to the point
where it is able to ripen right, or at all.;    Q I have begun getting white
hairs above my ears. They are kinkier than the rest of my hair. Will I
eventually have a head of frizzy white hair?;    A Researchers aren't sure
what makes some people's hair change texture when it goes gray. And it's hard
to say, based on a few hairs, how big a texture change you can expect.;    The
texture of your hair is determined in part by the shape of your hair
follicles, the little tubes in your skin from which the hair grows. Large
follicles produce coarse hair, while small follicles grow finer hair. Asians
have round, straight follicles, giving them straight, round hairs, while
blacks have flattened follicles that produce flattened hairs with a kinky
texture. Some people have curved follicles, which give them curly or wavy
hair.;    Hair texture is also affected by chemical properties of the keratin
protein that makes up the hair shaft.;    Your hair gets its color from
pigment-producing cells called melanocytes. As you grow older, the melanocytes
in some follicles will stop making pigment, and the hairs that grow from those
follicles will be white. The more white hairs you have, the grayer your hair
looks.;    Hair sometimes changes texture as it goes gray, but there has been
little research into why this is so, according to Kurt Stenn, a dermatologist
who studies hair at Yale University School of Medicine. It may be that in some
cases the melanocyte shut-down causes a change in the shape of the hair
follicle, or in the chemistry of the keratin protein.;    These changes could
occur in all or just some of your hair follicles, Stenn said, so it is hard to
say how dramatically different your silvering hair will be.  </TEXT>
