<LEADPARA>  I WOULD rather crawl over shards of glass than tell anyone how to dress. But
Kathy Willets has got to get rid of that bow in her hair.;   How in the world
does she expect us to believe nymphomania made her do it (and do it and do it)
with that bow in her hair?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BORDELLOS, DEMURE LOOK MAKES STRANGE BEDFELLOWS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Hagwood writes for the Fort Lauderdale, Fla., Sun-Sentinel  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (Kathy, 33, and Jeffrey Willets, 41, are accused of 35 crimes. Police say
they ran a bordello in their Tamarac, Fla., home. While Kathy Willets serviced
clients in her bedroom, her husband hid in the closet taking notes and
videotaping customers, police say.);   A woman I know said she recently ran
into Jeffrey and Kathy Willets in an Islamorada tiki bar.;   "First of all, I
was embarrassed to be in the same kind of bar as the Willetses," my buddy
sniffed.;   Once she got over that, she noticed that Kathy Willets' look was
more relaxed than her courtroom image. My friend reported that Willets was
dancing in a yellow midriff top and tight blue jeans; her hair was pulled
partially back in a barrette. She also wore less makeup than in court, but
this revealed sun-damaged skin.;   Isn't it amazing what you can notice "in a
glance"?;   I had to ask the next question: "Were you -- a woman -- offended
or perhaps even threatened by her obvious, um . . . sexual reputation?";  
"No," my buddy answered, calmly. "I was offended by her dye job. Mega-roots.";
  Meow. Remember, she said it, not me.;   Would a woman properly dressed,
coiffed and made up have to put up with the same scrutiny?;   Would she have
to contend with the occasional taunt from balconies -- "Hey, Kathy, I'm not on
that list, am I?" or "Give me back my business card"?;   I don't think so.;  
We asked Terri Lynn, president of a media-consulting firm in Fort Lauderdale,
how Willets could improve her image. Her company has prepared guests for
"Sally Jessy Raphael," "Donahue," CNN and FNN.;   "First, I'd like to get a
look at her closet," Lynn said during a telephone interview.;   "It's kind of
crowded in there already, Terri," I answered. "What next?";   "Both Kathy and
her husband are extremely good-looking people," Lynn said, ignoring my
interruption. "They're very attractive, and the issue pertains to sex. When I
see them in public, I just know they've been told to play down her sexuality;
hence the pearls and bows in her hair. They took the cue to the extreme.";  
But demure isn't working, Lynn said. The V-neck dresses Willets favors draw
attention to her breasts. She also hinted that only certain women can wear
aquamarine with white piping and get away with it.;   Lynn said there are ways
to dress for the public, showing respect without resorting to a nun's habit --
especially when you share no other nun-like habits.;   When Willets and her
husband were scheduled to appear on "The Oprah Winfrey Show," Lynn used her
knowledge of how that program can affect you (live audience and all) and how
people react to fashion (especially when one is accused of prostitution) and
came up with the following suggestions:;   (check)  Pants: "I'd want her legs
covered up. Women will feel better about her if their husbands don't look at
her legs. (I suggest) a pair of gray or navy slacks. Maybe an Anne Klein
herringbone or a small tweed.";   (check)  Bone-colored hose: "Bone because
with those she doesn't look like she's naked underneath.";   (check)  Soft,
cowl-neck turtleneck sweater: "It's a covered look, but not too stuffy or
librarian-like. Perhaps a soft color to blend with the pants.";   (check) 
Blazer: "To cover her breasts, so there's no real suggestion of sexuality.
She's a sexy woman; it comes through anyway.";   (check)  Hair: "Her hair
would really be up to her. People have seen her so much already, anything
drastic would be seen as an obvious ploy. Maybe she could do a French braid or
something to keep the hair off the face. She could use a navy bow, which is
her trademark.";   (Experts aren't always right. Lose the bow, I say!);  
(check)  Makeup: "Her makeup needs work. She wears a lot of light blue eye
shadow. She needs more colors that have the same tones as those found in her
skin.";   "Does it make her look cheap?" I asked.;   "Yes," said Lynn, before
tactfully changing the subject. "I think the final thing is a nice strand of
pearls, which I think she already has."  </TEXT>
