<LEADPARA>  'EVEN when the economy's fine, people are being fired and laid off," Phyllis
Macklin says. "There's much more of it now, and there's increased competition
for the jobs that are available, so you want to make sure that in every way
you have the edge.";    For Macklin's clients -- she's a partner in an
executive outplacement firm -- that starts with a long look in the mirror.
Some people, she says, "have advanced in their careers without ever paying
attention to how they dress." They've sailed along on pure competence, and
nobody's minded that they look like schlumps. Other people "have gotten
sloppy."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MIRROR, MIRROR, WHO'S HIRED?
APPEARANCES SPEAK FIRST AT INTERVIEWS, SO
SAY THE RIGHT THING, JOB ADVISER SAYS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Style
Distributed by Universal Press Syndicate.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     'Picky little details';  Either way, it's a problem. Because to get a job
-- particularly the kind of high-level corporate job her clients are angling
for -- it isn't enough to be competent. You also have to look competent. So
Macklin, over the years, has become a connoisseur of the million "picky little
details" that, in U.S. corporate culture, make a person look like a success.; 
  "For instance, a man makes a better impression in a navy-blue suit,
single-breasted, with a white shirt with a spread collar and long sleeves,
cotton because cotton won't pill at the collar, laundered and ironed.";   
You've heard that much before, but Macklin's just getting started: "A
crew-neck undershirt so the line doesn't show through the shirt. Tip of the
tie comes to the top or center of the belt buckle, back of the tie should go
through the label so the ends stay together. A belt that shows no signs of
wear or weight loss or gain. Well-shined, recently heeled black tie shoes.
Lightweight navy or black over-the-calf socks. No more than one ring on each
hand, and no other jewelry -- no tie tack, no bracelet, no necklace.";   
Nails should be "cut short and filed and clean. Hair should be trimmed . . .
above the ears and faces should be cleanshaven." To clients who are "real
attached to a beard or mustache," she says, "shave it until you're hired"
because "nobody ever doesn't get an offer for being cleanshaven.";    Clothes
should be "the best they can possibly afford." Carry "a leather portfolio or
slim briefcase. Pen in pocket sufficiently to the left so it doesn't stick out
of the jacket. Button the jacket when standing.";    Why do these minutiae
matter?;    An interviewer, Macklin says, will be looking at her clients "to
see if they fit, if they know the rules, if they can represent the company,"
if they can "deal with details." Subconsciously, the interviewer also will be
looking for "cues" that "demonstrate that person has been successful in the
past." This is why an unironed shirt, down-at-the-heel shoes, or a belt that
shows you've gained 20 pounds is a serious mistake: You want to impress the
guy, not make him feel sorry for you.;    More flexibility for women;  With so
much riding on appearance, Macklin advises clients to "wear what's better;
don't take second choice." Guys will say, "Isn't a blue shirt OK?" And it is
OK, but "a white shirt has a better impact.";    Women, she says, "have a
little more flexibility," but only a little. Macklin says they should wear
navy, gray or dark maroon conservative suits, a long-sleeved, high-necked
blouse in a complementary solid color -- white or cream or a pastel, "not red
or fuchsia." The skirt should cover the knee when they're seated in the
interview.;    The point is to "project professionalism," not sexiness.
Medium-heel leather pumps, no open toes or backs, and always stockings or
pantyhose, even in the summer. Simple earrings, not dangling. A pin or a
necklace. A watch. No more than one ring per hand. No more than one bracelet.;
   Makeup simple and soft, hair should be short, professional -- "not teased,
not bouffant, not bleached." Nails should be manicured, with light or clear
polish. Carry a briefcase, not a purse, and not both, because it's
"cumbersome," and "looks ungainly." If you wear a scarf or a necklace, make it
short enough to focus attention on your face.;    She reminds clients -- both
men and women -- to wear "glasses with up-to-date frames, and no tinting, no
photo-grays" because "you sit with someone and there's this barrier; they feel
like you're hiding." And when she says "up-to-date," she doesn't mean the
latest thing, necessarily. She's thinking of the guy who's been having new
lenses put in the same pair of beat-up Buddy Holly frames for the past 20
years because they haven't actually fallen apart yet. So he looks like a nerd,
a cheapskate or both.;    Macklin even tells clients when they have bad
breath, or body odor, or dandruff -- because if she doesn't, who will? "It's
very difficult to tell someone you work with that they have bad breath or
dandruff -- or that their perfume is too strong.";    Speaking of which, she
says you shouldn't wear any to an interview -- no perfume, no cologne, no
after-shave, no strong-smelling deodorant -- because what smells lovely to you
might smell awful to the interviewer.;    Make sure you get to the interview a
few minutes early so you have time to "wash your hands first, check yourself
out in the mirror, brush off your shoulders, comb your hair, make sure your
zippers are zipped and your buttons are buttoned.";    Then walk in, smile,
greet the interviewer by name, shake hands firmly and focus on the interview.;
   Once you've got the job, do a good job at it, and nobody'll mind if you
grow your mustache, wear blue shirts, come to work soaked in Giorgio, or have
bad breath. Well, maybe they'll mind. But they won't tell you.  </TEXT>
