<BYLINE>Alexandre the Great, King of Haute Coiffure ^By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bosom-baring models at Yves Saint Laurent and
the very proper late Duchess of Windsor had one thing in common _
perfectly coiffed tresses cared for by Alexandre de Paris.
   His hairstyles add zing to styles shown at nearly every major
fashion show in town _ from Saint Laurent to Chanel and from
Jean-Louis Scherrer to Emanuel Ungaro.
   During the shows, Alexandre and 20 assistants turn out
everything from ``snail'' chignons to lion locks on hundreds of
models.
   ``I have to know what's going on in the designers' minds,'' said
Alexandre during an interview in his office above the salon on the
Champs Elysees. ``I can't just play the matador with hair. It has
to be a logical part of fashion.''
   Known as king of coiffeurs, Alexandre also performs at royal
marriages such as Princess Caroline's first big wedding in Monaco.
He is on constant call for friends like Elizabeth Taylor and Sophia
Loren.
   He admires Loren ``who actually does her own hair almost every
day.''
   Born Louis Alexandre Raimondi to a family of vintners in the
Riviera seaport of St. Tropez, Alexandre started cutting hair in
1938 when he was 15, working for Antoine, the Cannes hairdresser
who was known as Coco Chanel's favorite.
   Alexandre was encouraged by the bushy-haired writer Colette, a
neighbor and friend of his grandmother ``who talked about Paris all
the time. I knew I had to go there.''
   After World War II, he met the Begum and the Duchess of Windsor,
who insisted he come to Paris, and he transferred his salon.
   Alexandre kept Jean Cocteau's wavy gray locks in line. The
artist-writer-film creator called Alexandre the sphinx, which
became the hair stylist's logo.
   When he met the Carita sisters the trio decided to set up shop
in 1952 on the rue du Faubourg Saint-Honore, not far from the
presidential Elysees Palace.
   Five years later, he branched off and hired a staff of 150,
becoming ``Alexandre de Paris.'' In 1980, he moved to the present
salon.
   With outlets throughout the United States and his own salon in
Houston, Alexandre's turnover is about $7 million a year _ much of
it from his accessory and cosmetics business.
   In November, he opened a small luxury accessory shop on the rue
du Faubourg Saint Honore with Francois Lesage, the master
embroiderer of haute couture.
   The whirlwind of fashion shows, royal weddings and openings are
all taken in stride, but some events are more memorable _ such as a
wedding in 1951 in Venice where he made a real splash.
   ``I'd done Princess Ira von Furstenburg's hair for her wedding
and was walking the gangplank from the gondola to attend the
ceremony.'' he recalled. ``Suddenly, I tripped and fell in the
Venice canal like a piece of lead.''
   Alexandre spends much of his free time with his two children
(neither in the hair business) and five grandchildren, often
spending holidays with them at his villa in St. Tropez.
   But his obsession remains with tresses, and he loves to give
advice: ``Long hair is for young girls or women who can afford to
have their hair done every day.'' he said. ``Most women should wear
something more modern, easier to care for.''
   As for older women letting their hair go gray, Alexandre doesn't
think much of it ``unless the woman has a lovely silvery sheen or a
snowy white color, as my grandmother did.''
   Though Alexandre is coiffeur to the stars, he also finds time
for ordinary customers ``provided they reserve well in advance.''
   A cut and restyling at the salon costs $35 dollars, inexpensive
by Paris standards. The price for styling by the master himself is
higher and is set according to the client.
   ``I've done the job so well on a few that their own husbands
didn't recognize them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
