<LEADPARA>  WHY ARE PEOPLE WITH ORANGE hair called redheads?;    NATURALLY WE TURNED TO
THE COLOR Association of the United States for help. This is a real
organization. They give advice to the fashion industry. Associate director
Margaret Walch confirmed our suspicions: Redheads are actually orangeheads.
"The hue is orange, but we call it red," Walch said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THAT'S WHY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The Standard Color Reference of America lists 198 individual colors. One is
"henna," which as a hair coloring is designed to make someone a redhead, but
which Walch describes as "terra cotta orange." We asked her to clarify that
and she said it was "rust colored." Unfortunately the chromatically illiterate
Why staff comprehends only red, blue, green, yellow, orange, brown and purple,
and so we insisted on a simpler description, finally getting: "It's a
brown-orange.";    So why do we call it red?;    "I think there is a
psychological connotation here. Red has positive connotations, as opposed to
orange, which has a banal, pedestrian quality," she said. "Red implies more
energy, more drama.";    Incidentally, if you've ever wondered why fashionable
people use such absurd terms for colors -- you know, "cardinal" instead of
"red" -- it's because those are the official colors according to the Standard
Color Reference of America. There is no red in there. But there is "scarlet"
and "geranium." There's also "flax," "toast brown," "grotto blue," "amber
light," "mosstone," which is green with a touch of gray, and the bizarre
"leghorn." It's a sort of phlegm yellow. To use an unofficial term.;  GUESS
AGAIN; DIANA RIGG WOULD PROBABLY RATHER not be reminded of her 1973 NBC
sitcom. What was it called?;    A. Diana;    B. The Girl With Something Extra;
   C. Lotsa Luck;    D. Needles and Pins;    E. Roll Out (Answer below);
ANSWER: A. For that matter, Sally Field and Teri Garr would probably like to
forget B, on which they appeared.  </TEXT>
