<HEAD>State Fair Finds Steer Was Dyed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Coloring the ...' to CLARIFY that steer
won second-place ribbon; SUBS last graf to RESTORE first reference to Fouts.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are trying to determine
whether the Ohio State Fair's grand champion steer, Hank, also goes
by the name Carl, a ribbon winner at an Illinois farm show.
   The key piece of evidence is a patch of white hair on Hank's
underside that had been dyed black, an Ohio state fair official said.
   Coloring the animal's hide is itself a violation, but fair
officials are also investigating whether Hank was shown as Carl
three weeks earlier at the Iroquois County Fair in Illinois, where
it won a second-place ribbon.
   If the allegation is true, the prize steer violates the rules of
both fairs because it was shown by different families and because it
fails to meet ownership requirements. An exhibitor must own and care
for the animal as of Jan. 1 to show at either fair.
   The Ohio 4-H, the Future Farmers of America and the state fair
have been gathering evidence for more than two weeks.
   When officials examined the Ohio fair's grand champion steer
after the competition Aug. 14, a dark dye was wiped from the steer's
abdomen. The dark-colored hairs have grown out.
   ``It is white,'' Jim Goard, director of livestock and agriculture
for the state fair, said Wednesday. ``It needs to match the spots on
pictures of the animal from Illinois, but it appears to be white,
and coloring an animal is a major violation in itself.''
   A white spot was visible in photos of Carl, shown by Jeremy
Simmons, 12, at the Iroquois County Fair on July 24.
   Hank was shown by Susan Shealy, 17, of Tiro, who could be forced
to forfeit her first-place ribbon and the $28,000 price the
Angus-cross steer brought at the fair. Her family could be banned
from showing at the fair for three or more years.
   Jeremy, of Donovan, Ill., also could face a penalty.
   Both families deny any wrongdoing.
   Hank has been in the custody of Ohio State University while his
hair grows out. Investigators visited OSU's beef barn Tuesday to
photograph the steer in postures similar to the stances shown in
photos of the Illinois winner.
   Jeremy's father, Donald Kopsell, has said Carl was destroyed
after eating tainted corn.
   State fair rules require investigators to make a recommendation
to the fair's Beef, Sheep and Swine Committee. The committee must
recommend action to the nine-member Ohio Expositions Commission,
which runs the fair.
   ``If they call for a hearing, all parties will be notified and
given a chance to tell their side of the story,'' Jack Foust,
general manager of the fair.
</TEXT>
