<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; FASHION; CLEANUP; BUSINESS; MAN; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  On the wall above the counter at Harold Henry Hulbert's central San Jose shop
is a plaque honoring his 50 years in the dry cleaning business.;   The plaque
is 10 years old. He's 87.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  OCTOGENARIAN STILL CLEANS UP IN BUSINESS
S.J. DRY CLEANER IS THE WIZARD OF STAIN REMOVAL
TRADITIONAL METHODS THE RULE AT THIS FAMILY-RUN
BUSINESS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Hulbert shows up each day at a job from which he could have retired decades
ago. Instead, he presses on, as they say in the cleaning business.;   By
Hulbert's count, more than 15 million shirts have been washed, dried, pressed,
tagged and shipped out the door of his Diamond Laundry &amp; Cleaners since he
opened it in 1931. That doesn't count the trousers, dresses, suits, vests,
jackets, blankets, draperies, pillows, napkins and tablecloths his San Carlos
Street shop has rejuvenated over the years.;   He has seen every kind of stain
on every kind of material. He has been beaten by a few. He has preserved
wedding dresses, saved family heirlooms and rescued items vital to a child's
security.;   "His real joy right now is stuffed animals," said Mary Hulbert,
Harold's wife of 27 years. "Sometimes a mother will come in with a little
teddy bear and say, 'Can we have it tonight, because he won't go to sleep
without it.' ";   Hulbert will get it done, said Mary Hulbert, who is 69.;  
This is a business run the way businesses used to be run. Harold, Mary and
Mary's son manage the operation, at San Carlos and Delmas Avenue. Harold
Hulbert said it's the last family-owned cleaners in San Jose.;   Harold
Hulbert, a thin man with thinner gray hair and a neatly pressed shirt,
explains that he and his wife have been successful in love and business for
one simple reason:;   "It's just my good nature.";   This makes Mary Hulbert,
a gregarious woman with carrot-colored hair and a perpetual smile, laugh so
hard that she almost falls out of her chair. It turns out Harold Hulbert can
be, or at least act, a little grumpy. A privilege of age, said Sandy Hazzard,
who at three years on the payroll is a newcomer.;   Diamond cleaners doesn't
rely on catchy slogans. About the best Hulbert can muster is: "We don't do any
cheap work," and, "If we can't do it, throw it away.";   There is, of course,
"Miss Careful," a Diamond cleaners mascot of sorts that the Hulberts aren't
quite sure what to do with. An advertising salesman created her years ago,
when Hulbert first listed the business in the Yellow Pages. Now her faceless
figure and the message "Miss Careful Works Here" grace the Diamond cleaners
billboard just outside Hulbert's office.;   "She had a face," Mary Hulbert
explained with a hint of the accent she brought with her from Scotland in
1946. "But now we don't know what to do. Maybe give her a young look, but
she's not so young.";   Not much is young around the Diamond cleaners. The
wall clock that hung at the cleaners' first location now hangs at the
40-year-old San Carlos location. The old building and the stretch of Grant
Street it was on are both buried under Interstate 280.;   A tour of the back
shop conjures up images of a museum exhibit on the Industrial Revolution. The
hissing of the steam presses and the shooshing of the compressors can be
detected a half block away. Dirty laundry is delivered to a back door. It is
subjected to a series of hulking contraptions that line the back room's
concrete floor. There are the gigantic washers, each looking like a space
capsule tipped on its side. The big green roller machine dries, flattens, then
spits out the items. There are the pressing machines with the pull-down tops
-- the kind the Three Stooges constantly got their heads caught in. Finally,
there are the household-variety irons, used by workers to eliminate remaining
wrinkles and press in creases.;   It's the attention to detail, Mary Hulbert
said, that differentiates Diamond cleaners from what she calls "the 99-cent
people." Sure, the modern, mass-production cleaners can beat Diamond's $1.70
charge for a shirt, but they can't beat the Diamond-pressed creases, she
said.;   Harold Hulbert doesn't care what the upstarts charge.;   "I don't
worry about what the competitors do," he said. "I worry about what we need to
operate.";   He didn't learn that in business school. Harold Hulbert was one
of 11 children whose mother brought him up on "whiskey and milk" once his
father died, Mary Hulbert explained. School outlived its usefulness in sixth
grade, so Harold Hulbert went to work -- as a paperboy, then in the press room
at the Santa Rosa Democrat, at a laundry in Oakland, as a projectionist at the
California Theater in San Jose and finally at his own business, which he
started with a $5,000 bank loan in the middle of the Depression.;   It's a job
he would keep for another 60 years if he could. And with Harold Henry Hulbert,
you just never know.  </TEXT>
